        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> This is working as intended. When the completion menu is already open, typing more keys filter the correct completion instead of starting a new one.\n\nThe current behavior doesn’t seem correct in this scenario. When I type `.c`, there is a valid completion item available, yet the menu does not display it.\n\nAs shown in the GIF, I need to exit and re-enter insert mode to see the completion. Ideally, the menu should automatically update and display any available completions without leaving insert mode.\n\nTo illustrate further, here’s another example:\n\n[https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2d3053b4-cc31-48f8-b0af-2a5fb1df055b](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2d3053b4-cc31-48f8-b0af-2a5fb1df055b)\n\nIn this GIF, I type `.container`. The autocomplete menu appears initially, but when I type `.c`, the menu stops showing completions—even though the Emmet language server provides completions for every subsequent input (e.g., `.c`, `.co`, `.con`, `.cont`).\n\nThis seems inconsistent with expected behavior, as the menu should remain visible and update as valid completions are available.\n\n---\n\n> `autocomplete` is from Vim.\n\nSorry, I wasn't aware that `autocomplete` is from Vim.",
